        <h2>The Bare-Minimum</h2>

        <ol class="inhalt-links">
            <li>Bro/Sis/NB Sibling. Wake the fuck up, samurai. We have a city to burn/a task to do.</li>
            <li>Pick ONE task. Not "tOdAy i WiLl fIx mY lIfE" One. Single. Thing.</li>
            <li>Now cut it down until it’s as small as your will to live</li>
            <li>Set a timer. Goal: do something for 30 minutes. Then pause. </li>
            <li>You even like doing this, you have fun coding and writing and shit, just *Shia LeBauf* "DO IT!"</li>
            <li>Reward yourself like a toddler: snack, sticker, song, cigarette.</li>
            <li>You got this, sweetie.</li>
            <li>Rinse, reboot, repeat.</li>
            <li>Bro, is that peanut butter? And a giant spoon? Okay, you do you.</li>
        </ol>

        <p class="inhalt-links">
            Procrasti-net philosophy: motivation is a scam, and discipline is shame wearing a suit. Capitalism thrives on you being tired, scared, and convinced your worth is measured in output. If you’re exhausted and stuck, congrats, the machine is working as intended.
            <br><br>
            Your brain isn’t broken, the system is. You’re a human being with a nervous system, not a machine. If you wantto join the fight on capitalism, check out Andrea Wu's Website.
            <br><br>
            The gods have allowed you to live another day, now go make it everybody else's problem.
            <br><br>
            Do it because Future You deserves a slightly less awful timeline. Tiny steps count. Bare minimum counts. “I showed up” counts. Consistency is not a personality, it’s a feedback loop. Build the loop.
            <br><br>
            If you crash, you didn’t fail. Drink water. Breathe. Cut the task in half again. Choose the smallest button. Repeat. The goal isn’t perfection. The goal is staying alive and stealing your life back one minute at a time.
        </p>
    </div>
